### Design notes

- **Armoured Recruit** is a flex Armour-grant body — 2E for 200/300 + a freely-targeted 100 Armour buff. The targeted Armour is the key design: it lets the player aim the buff at the Knight (Iron Resolve / Unbreakable / Bastion Rune compounding), at a fragile Demon body B3 wants to keep alive, or at the Recruit itself in a pinch. Numbers benchmarked against Quartermaster (3E 200/400 + +100 Armour per summon aura) — Recruit trades the aura for a one-shot 100 grant at a 1E discount and 100 HP less.
- **Shield Bearer** is the Formation-anchor — a 3E 200/200 Human whose Formation grants **adjacent friendly minions** GUARD and 200 Armour (Shield Bearer itself does not gain GUARD or Armour — the buff explicitly goes outward). The body is intentionally fragile (200 HP) so the player commits to a positioning play; in exchange the adjacent pair receives a permanent 200 Armour buff plus GUARD (no expiry). With the Knight as the Formation partner this is the canonical "fortify the Knight" play for B1; with Rank Breaker or another Demon adjacent, it doubles up the Demon side of the board in B3. Note: Shield Bearer is a Human, so Formation only fires when adjacent to another Human (per §2 same-race rule) — pairing with Demons does **not** trigger this.
- **Bonebreaker** is the **physical-then-AB combo** card. Rename from "Abyssal Breaker (demon)" was deliberate — the original name collided with the B3 branch ID `abyssal_breaker`. Resolution order on ON PLAY: **deal 200 PHYSICAL damage first, then apply 200 Armour Break**. This order is intentional and is a **soft nerf** versus the alternative (AB-first) — the damage lands against the target's *current* Armour, so a 200-Armour minion takes the 200 damage reduced by Armour math to the 100 floor, *then* eats the 200 AB as a residual debuff. Against an unarmoured target the 200 PHYSICAL lands at full 200, and the 200 AB drives Armour to −200 (a deep debuff that converts to flat bonus damage on every future incoming physical hit — see ruling note on negative Armour). The order makes Bonebreaker an **enabler** rather than a finisher: the AB it leaves behind is what makes follow-up attacks bite, not the on-play damage itself. 3E for 200/300 Demon + this on-play matches Void Netter (2E 100/300 + 200 single-target damage) — Bonebreaker pays +1E for +100 ATK, +1 race tier (Demon), and the 200 AB residual.
- **Shattering Volley** is the board-wide AB + flat-damage spell. Each enemy (minions and enemy hero — see ruling note below) gets 100 AB applied first (Armour can be driven negative), then takes a flat 100 PHYSICAL hit. The "100 AB always lands a full 100" reading is intentional — there's no scaling damage based on Armour stripped, just a clean AoE: −100 Armour, then 100 damage. Against unarmoured targets the AB stack lingers as a flat-bonus-damage debuff for future attacks; against armoured targets the strip + hit combo is a clean trade. PHYSICAL school means the 100 damage routes through Armour math (§2 linter rules) — a 200-Armour target loses 100 Armour to AB, then takes the 100 hit reduced to the 100 floor against the remaining 100 Armour. 2M cost matches Abyssal Plague (2M / 100 AoE damage + AoE corruption) — Shattering Volley trades the corruption rider for an AB rider.
- **Battle Drillmaster** is the **"stuck Formation" rescue card** — 4E for 200/500 dual-tag body whose ON PLAY fires every dormant FORMATION minion on the board, ignoring the same-race adjacency requirement. The design intent is **not** to bypass Formation setup work; it's to rescue Formation minions that got placed at the left- or right-most slot and have no neighbor on one side, or pairs that were broken when an intervening Demon was summoned between two Humans. Each Formation effect still fires only once per pair (§2 rule unchanged) — Drillmaster cashes in *dormant* Formations, not re-triggers used ones. The 4E cost is the price for the cash-out — not a cheap utility, but a turn 4-5 swing play that rewards decks that overcommit FORMATION minions early without perfect positioning. Drillmaster's own dual-tag (Human/Demon) means it can't accidentally block a same-race Formation it just triggered. Stacks naturally with Knight T0 in B1 (a stuck Knight with no Human neighbor still fires its +200 Armour/+200 HP via Drillmaster); B2/B3 Knights don't have FORMATION so they're untouched.
- **Rank Breaker** is the 2E Demon Formation seed — drop it adjacent to any Demon (including the dual-tag Knight in B2 or the Demon Knight in B3), and on Formation trigger it strips 100 Armour from **all enemy minions** (not enemy hero — see ruling note). 2E for 300/200 + a board-wide AB Formation trigger is intentionally **pushed** for the slot, justified by: (a) Formation requires same-race adjacency, so the trigger isn't automatic on summon (player needs to set up a Demon pair); (b) one-shot trigger per Formation pair — the AB doesn't repeat; (c) glass-cannon stat line (300 ATK / 200 HP, dies to 200 damage). Replaces Hold the Line because it gives Korrath a *minion-bodied* Formation payoff rather than a one-shot spell — better long-term board presence.
- **Bastion Rune** is the Korrath Rune (Common Pool pattern mirrors Soul Rune / Flesh Rune). Simplified to: at start of turn, give 100 Armour to a random friendly minion. No hero-Armour threshold, no scaling — clean and durable. Per-turn cost is zero, so no self-cleanup needed (unlike Flesh Rune's upkeep). The 100 Armour drip is incremental but compounds heavily in B1 with Iron Resolve (each tick = +100 ATK on Humans) and Unbreakable (Knight ticks doubled to 200). Trade-off: occupies a rune slot, which B2's `runeforge_strike` wants for its own rune generation — running Bastion Rune in B2 means one less slot for rune-board fuel.
- **Creeping Blight** is the corruption-applying spell — a deliberate departure from the §11 "no corruption in common" rule. Justification: the Abyss Order faction-core corruption sources (Abyss Cultist, Corruption Weaver, Abyssal Plague) all apply to *minions only* or are *random target*. Creeping Blight is the first **single-target, hero-or-minion-targeting** corruption spell available to Korrath without Branch 3 talents. The card's branch-fit is honestly skewed — B3 amplifies it heavily through Path of Corruption (+100 VOID_CORRUPTION dmg per stack on target) and Corrupting Presence (each stack strips 100 Armour). For B1/B2 it functions as a generic 2M / 300 / spot-damage spell — playable, not synergistic. Damage school is VOID_CORRUPTION; per §2 (linter-updated Armour rules) VOID lineage bypasses Armour entirely, so the 300 damage lands full regardless of target Armour. Numbers benchmarked against Void Bolt (2M / 500 / hero-only) and Flesh Rend (2M / 300 / minion-or-hero + Flesh scaling) — Creeping Blight matches Flesh Rend's damage and target flexibility, swapping the Flesh-scale upside for a corruption-stack rider.
- **Banner of the Order** is the **dual-race buff spell** at the cheap-utility tier (1M, matching Dark Empowerment / Fiendish Pact / Void Spawning). Both halves resolve on cast, **stamped onto each qualifying minion individually** (not an aura — see ruling note): (a) every friendly Human currently on board gains 100 Armour immediately (one-shot stat grant); (b) every friendly Demon currently on board receives a permanent on-attack rider — for the rest of that Demon's life, each of its attacks resolves damage first, *then* applies 100 Armour Break to the target. Demons summoned *after* the cast do **not** receive the rider; re-casting Banner on a refilled board is the way to re-arm. Timing on the Demon half: post-damage residual, matching `path_of_shattering` — they stack cleanly to 150 AB residual per attack after damage. This timing convention is shared across the whole AB-via-attack family (Bonebreaker, Banner, `path_of_shattering`) — AB is always a *residual debuff that softens future hits*, never a same-strike amplifier. Banner's rider is idempotent per minion (re-cast doesn't double-stamp the same Demon). **Branch fit is strong in all three:** B1 turns +100 Armour into +100 ATK on every friendly Human via Iron Resolve (Armour scales harder here than elsewhere); B2's dual-tag Knight eats *both* halves (+100 Armour as a Human, +100 AB rider as a Demon) — most efficient single spell on a B2 Knight; B3 stacks the AB rider with `path_of_shattering` for 150 AB/attack on every Demon, feeding Shattering Doom. Naming continues the §10 "Order" family (Squire of the Order, Order Conscript, Order Footman) reinforcing Korrath's commander-of-an-army flavor.

**Ruling notes (cross-card):**

- **Shattering Volley "all enemies"** includes enemy hero (per Abyssal Plague / Flesh Eruption convention). AB on enemy hero is meaningful in Korrath because the hero has an Armour stat (per §6 + task 007).
- **Rank Breaker "all enemy minions"** is minion-only (deliberate — keeps the 2E pushed-cost defensible). If you want hero AB too, bump cost to 3E.
- **Bonebreaker resolution order:** damage first → AB second. This is intentionally the *opposite* of the on-attack resolution order from §2, and acts as a soft nerf: the damage hits the target's full current Armour, then the AB leaves a residual debuff for follow-up attacks. The AB on this card is an enabler for future hits, not an amplifier of the on-play damage.
- **Shattering Volley negative Armour:** the AB phase of Shattering Volley can drive a target's Armour below zero. Negative Armour is a real game state — per §2 Armour Break "If Armour Break exceeds Armour value, excess converts to flat bonus physical damage," so negative Armour acts as a flat-bonus-damage debuff on incoming physical hits until the target climbs back to zero Armour. **Same-cast interaction matters here:** Shattering Volley applies AB **before** its 100 PHYSICAL damage, so each enemy's damage payload *does* benefit from the negative-Armour state Volley just created — a 0-Armour minion takes Volley to −100 Armour, then takes 100 PHYSICAL boosted by 100 flat-bonus-damage = 200 total. Bonebreaker is the **opposite** ordering (damage first, then AB), so Bonebreaker's own 200 PHYSICAL does **not** benefit from the 200 AB it leaves behind — that AB only matters for follow-up attacks. This asymmetry is intentional and is the core distinction between "AB-as-amplifier" cards (Shattering Volley) and "AB-as-residual" cards (Bonebreaker, Banner's rider, `path_of_shattering`).
- **Battle Drillmaster cascade scope:** fires *only* FORMATION minions whose specific pair-effect hasn't triggered yet (per §2 — Formation is a one-time permanent trigger per pair). A FORMATION minion that has already triggered with one neighbor doesn't fire again. Drillmaster also doesn't fire its **own** Formation, since it doesn't have FORMATION as a keyword.
- **PHYSICAL damage school** on Bonebreaker / Shattering Volley: per linter-updated §2, PHYSICAL goes **through Armour** (only VOID lineage + TRUE_DMG bypass). This is intentional — these are physical AB-stacking cards, and the AB they apply on the same cast is what makes the physical land. Cards that ignore the new Armour gating belong in the VOID lineage (Creeping Blight, etc.).
- **Banner of the Order rider scope:** the Demon AB rider is **not an aura** — it is stamped onto each Demon present at cast time as a per-minion property. Demons summoned after the cast are unaffected; if every original Demon dies the rider is gone from the board until Banner is cast again. This is distinct from an aura (which would re-apply to new bodies entering board state) and distinct from a passive talent like `path_of_shattering` (which is a faction-wide listener tied to the talent, not to specific minions). The rider is idempotent — a Demon already carrying the rider doesn't gain a second from a re-cast.
- **AB-on-attack timing convention:** every "AB applied via *attack*" effect — `path_of_shattering`, Banner of the Order's per-minion rider, Bonebreaker's ON PLAY combo — resolves **after** the strike's damage. AB from these sources is a *post-damage residual debuff* that softens future hits, never a same-strike amplifier. This is the rule for **attack-driven AB**. Spell-cast AB is a separate family: Shattering Volley applies AB **before** its damage (same cast), so the negative-Armour from its strip *does* boost the damage component of that same cast. Rule of thumb: **attack triggers → AB-after, spell casts → AB-when-the-spell-text-says** (Volley says "Apply AB to all enemies, then deal damage," so AB is before damage; if a future spell says "deal damage, then apply AB," that one would be after — cards spell their own order). This convention makes Shattering Doom (B3 T3) the natural payoff valve for attack-driven AB: across multiple Demon attacks on the same target, AB accumulates without consuming Armour, building toward detonation on death.

